            <p>
                This interpretation leads to believe that my
                equalizer from Exercise 8 is, in fact, 
                the correct one.  The product also 
                gives me a way of defining the equalizer
                more explicitly:
                <me>e(x) =
                    \begin{cases} 
              \langle x_1,y_1 \rangle &amp; \text{if}\, x = x_1 \\
              \langle x_3,y_4 \rangle &amp; \text{if}\, x = x_3 \\
              \langle x_4,y_4 \rangle &amp; \text{if}\, x = x_4
           \end{cases}
                </me>
                
